--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

"COMMERCIAL USE" IS STRICTLY PROHIBITED without explicit written permission 
from the copyright holder. Commercial use includes but is not limited to:

1. PROHIBITED COMMERCIAL ACTIVITIES:
   a) Incorporating this code into commercial products or services
   b) Using this code to provide consulting or paid professional services
   c) Selling, leasing, or licensing this software or derivatives thereof
   d) Using this code in for-profit research or development
   e) Using this code to generate commercial data or insights for sale
   f) Creating derivative works for commercial distribution
   g) Using this code in any capacity that generates revenue or commercial advantage
   h) Including this code in proprietary or closed-source products

2. ACADEMIC AND RESEARCH INSTITUTION RESTRICTIONS:
   Non-commercial use by academic institutions is permitted ONLY when:
   a) Research results are published openly and publicly
   b) No industry funding or commercial partnerships are involved in the 
      specific research project using this code
   c) Results and insights are not provided to commercial partners
   d) The institution does not use the code to fulfill commercial contracts
   e) The research is purely academic with no commercial applications pending

3. GRAY AREAS REQUIRING EXPLICIT PERMISSION:
   The following uses REQUIRE prior written approval:
   a) Use by government contractors or defense industry
   b) Use in projects with mixed academic/commercial funding
   c) Use in "proof of concept" work for potential commercial applications
   d) Use by non-profit organizations engaged in commercial activities
   e) Personal use by employees of for-profit companies as part of their work
   f) Use in open-source projects that have commercial sponsorship

4. PERMITTED NON-COMMERCIAL USES:
   a) Academic research at non-profit educational institutions (subject to 2a-e)
   b) Personal educational use and learning
   c) Teaching and coursework at academic institutions
   d) Purely hobbyist/recreational use with no commercial gain
   e) Open-source non-commercial projects (with proper attribution)

